 seeds and I am NOT paying upwards of $4 for a loaf.  Not a lot of recipes that aren&#8217;t labor-intensive for this. Do you think I could sub rye flour for the wheat? Or might it be too heavy? Also, can I continue to use regular granulated RedStar yeast, or buy the bread machine variety? Thanks, again.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"reply\">\n\t\t\t<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2010/12/no-knead-ciabatta/?replytocom=85420#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm(\"comment-85420\", \"85420\", \"respond\", \"13392\")'>Reply</a>\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<ul class=\"children\">\n\n\t<li class=\"comment byuser comment-author-beth bypostauthor odd alt depth-2\" id=\"comment-85450\">\n\n\t\t\n\t\t<div class=\"comment-header\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"comment-author vcard\">\n\t\t\t\t<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/254ccb2a309b73f73d1c117c28ea4d03?s=48&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />\t\t\t\t<cite class=\"fn\"><a href='http://www.budgetbytes.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Beth M</a></cite> <span class=\"says\">says:</span>\t\t \t</div>\n\n\t\t\t<div class=\"comment-meta commentmetadata\">\n\t\t\t\t<a href=\"http://www.budgetbytes.com/2010/12/no-knead-ciabatta/#comment-85450\">09.08.13 at 4:48 pm</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"comment-content\">\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t<p>You know, I&#8217;ve never baked with rye flour so I&#8217;m not really sure. The yeast needs to be &#8220;instant&#8221; or &#8220;bread machine&#8221; or &#8220;rapid-rise&#8221; yeast. Those varieties can be added to a recipe dry without mixing with water first. Regular yeast or &#8220;active dry&#8221; needs to be proofed in warm water before adding to a recipe.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"reply\">\n\t\t\t<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2010/12/no-knead-ciabatta/?replytocom=85450#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm(\